<module>
    <h>còmhla</h>
    <p><g>còmhla</g>
        <en>together</en> is an <a href="?xx=prepositions/adverbs">adverb</a>.</p>

    <section>
        <h>dependents</h>
        <section>
            <h>complement</h>
            <module id="coomhla_ri">
                <h>còmhla ri ...</h>
                <p><g>còmhla</g> can occur with the preposition <a href="?gd=ri"><g>ri</g></a> as
                    its complement – <g>còmhla ri ...</g>
                    <en>along/together with</en>.</p>
                <p>Some examples with proper nouns – <xl>
                        <li>
                            <gd>A bheil an cat a’ cluich <m>còmhla ri Seònaid</m> air an làr?</gd>
                            <tr>Is the cat playing along with Janet on the floor?</tr>
                            <ref text="617">td. 14</ref>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <gd>Tha an cù <m>còmhla ri Calum</m> anns an achadh an diugh.</gd>
                            <tr>The dog is along with Calum in the field today.</tr>
                            <ref text="617">td. 15</ref>
                        </li>
                    </xl>
                </p>
                <p>Some examples with common nouns – <xl>
                        <li>
                            <gd>Nach robh Calum agus Màiri a’ cluich <m>còmhla ris a’ chù</m>? Cha
                                robh, bha iad anns a’ bhaile.</gd>
                            <tr>Weren’t Malcolm and Mary playing with the dog? No, they weren’t,
                                they were in the town.</tr>
                            <ref text="617">td. 21 [230]</ref>
                        </li>
                    </xl>
                </p>
            </module>
        </section>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h>uses</h>
        <section id="uses-pred">
            <h>predicate</h>
            <p><g>còmhla</g> can be used as the predicate of <a href="?gd=bi"><g>bi</g></a>
                <en>be</en>.</p>
            <p>Some examples – <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Càit a bheil an cù? Tha e <m>còmhla</m> ri Calum.</gd>
                        <tr>Where is the dog? It is with Calum.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 19–20</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl></p>
            <p>Some examples with multiple predicates – <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Tha an cat anns an taigh <m>còmhla</m> ri Seònaid.</gd>
                        <tr>The cat is in the house along with Janet.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 14</ref>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Chan eil Seònaid anns an achadh <m>còmhla</m> ri Seumas.</gd>
                        <tr>Janet is not in the field slong with James.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 14</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
        <section id="uses-mod">
            <h>modifier</h>
            <p><g>còmhla</g> can be used as a (comitative) modifier of a verb.</p>
            <p>Some examples – <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>A bheil an cat a’ cluich <m>còmhla</m> ri Seònaid air an làr?</gd>
                        <tr>Is the cat playing along with Janet on the floor?</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 14</ref>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Nach robh Calum agus Màiri a’ cluich <m>còmhla ris a’ chù</m>? Cha robh,
                            bha iad anns a’ bhaile.</gd>
                        <tr>Weren’t Malcolm and Mary playing with the dog? No, they weren’t, they
                            were in the town.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 21 [230]</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
    </section>


